        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require both high CO J=3-2 line and continuum sensitivity, so split one baseband into 0.847km/s channels for the goal of CO detection, leaving the other three at low spectral resolution to retain continuum sensitivity. The compact nature of the disk means that the expected velocity width is ~32km/s, so the line will be easily resolved.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The HD 98800 disk is extremely compact (&lt;0.2-0.3" radius), so requires very high resolution to image and will not be resolved out. Specifically, the disk structure predicted by n-body simulations finds a gap between 7-9au (Fig. 1 in proposal). Detecting this gap, and a warp predicted to exist from reddening of the inner binary, therefore sets the resolution to ~2au, which is 0.05" at the distance of 45pc. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require high spatial resolution (2.3au, C36-7) to discern the spatial dust structure, and the sensitivity is then set by detection of CO in a narrow debris disk-like production scenario. The spectral sensitivity is sufficient to obtain our continuum imaging goals.

Our sensitivity is driven by a test of whether the O/CO ratio for HD 98800 is the same as for  Pic, so we require a 3 detection of a narrow CO belt for O/CO=5, for Tex=Tdust (Fig. 2 in proposal). This detection requires a sensitivity of 1.9mJy/beam in a 0.85km/s channel (1.5h on source, 4.4h with overheads). Our calculation of this sensitivity already includes spectral and spatial integration (as in Matra et al 2015), we have entered 5.7mJy/beam in the OT to ensure the S/N is &gt;3. We can also rule out O/CO&lt;1 for a wide disk, achieving our main science goal.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
