    <prp:abstract>We propose 4.4h of Band 7 continuum and CO observations of the archetype of extreme warm dust systems; HD 98800 (~10Myr, 45pc, where 10% of the systems total luminosity is thermally emitted by dust). Recently detected atomic oxygen may be a CO dissociation product, coming from the recent onset of cometary or planetary collisions, the birth of a debris disk. This tantalizing prospect is tempered by the possibility that the disk is in the late stages of dispersing its primordial gas disk. Our main goal is therefore to distinguish between these scenarios, shedding light on the uncertain nature of planetary systems as they emerge from the primordial disk phase. As a young multiple star system with known orbits, HD 98800 is also the only nearby system that can serve as a benchmark for quantitative modeling of disk dynamics in multiple systems. Overall, HD 98800 is one of the richest nearby stellar systems in terms of the science achievable from a single system.</prp:abstract>
